[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_wHceqlrPcCcEpy4OHeKLXx7P|fc_0acc0053d5c02462016a4058503e9c8196a59507e4c152d004", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "rg: buildSrc: No such file or directory (os error 2)\nrg: src: No such file or directory (os error 2)\n./build.gradle:150:            \"generateDynamicAccessReport\",\n./build.gradle:151:            \"generateDynamicAccessCoverageReport\",\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `library-update-request` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that updates metadata/tests for an existing library version, especially generated PRs titled like `[GenAI] Improve coverage for group:artifact:version using gpt-5.5`. Focus on preserving dynamic-access coverage percentage between versions, verifying reporter-requested metadata is present and exercised by tests, and applying the relevant test/scope rules from new-library reviews without requiring a minimum new-library dynamic-access coverage threshold.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:17:- Do not require `library-new-request`'s minimum dynamic-access threshold. A library update can be acceptable with low coverage if the percentage did not regress and the requested issue work is covered.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:18:- A requested version that reports zero dynamic-access calls (for example `dynamicAccess.totalCalls == 0`, or a `{}` `reachability-metadata.json` with no claimed dynamic-access behavior) does not give enough information to judge whether metadata is unnecessary or whether a metadata-entry-count drop is meaningful. Dynamic-access stats can miss metadata required through transitive dependencies. Do not escalate a shallow test, a test that exercises behavior outside the library's responsibility, or a metadata-entry-count drop to a blocking issue or `human-intervention` for such a library. The native execution gate and any issue-requested metadata gate still apply.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:57:4. Check dynamic-access coverage percentage.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:62:   - Compare the top-level dynamic-access percentage/ratio. Do not require covered call counts or total call counts to match, and do not block just because one version has fewer dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:63:   - A lower coverage percentage for the requested version is blocking unless the PR gives a concrete explanation, such as upstream removal of reachable dynamic-access sites or an intentionally narrower supported surface.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:66:   - Do not apply the `library-new-request` rule that dynamic-access coverage must be above 20%.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:87:   - When the requested version reports zero dynamic-access calls, do not escalate test-depth concerns (a shallow test, or one exercising behavior outside the library's responsibility) to a blocking issue or `human-intervention`. The zero-call report gives too little information to judge metadata relevance, so depth-of-coverage objections carry little signal. The native execution gate and any issue-requested metadata gate still apply.\n./skills/review-library-update-request/SKILL.md:125:- For coverage percentage drops: say that `library-update-request` PRs must not reduce dynamic-access coverage percentage between versions, cite old and new percentages, and ask for restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-java-run-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR described as `fixes-java-run-fail` or one that fixes Java/JVM runtime test failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the Java runtime fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring the dynamic-access coverage percentage does not drop by more than 20 percentage points between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair tests, dependencies, or narrow runtime setup after an existing library version compiles, but the JVM-based test fails when it runs. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library already exists, so the goal is to restore Java runtime behavior for the new version while preserving meaningful test and dynamic-access coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:20:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate, compared by percentage only. Do not treat changes in absolute covered or total call counts as a drop. The new version should not report a coverage percentage more than 20 percentage points lower than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:21:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:23:- A new version that reports zero dynamic-access calls (for example `dynamicAccess.totalCalls == 0`, or a `{}` `reachability-metadata.json` with no claimed dynamic-access behavior) does not give enough information to judge whether metadata is unnecessary or whether a metadata-entry-count drop is meaningful. Dynamic-access stats can miss metadata required through transitive dependencies. Do not report a metadata-entry-count drop, and do not flag a shallow test or a test that exercises behavior outside the library's responsibility, as a blocking issue or `human-intervention` for such a library. The Java runtime fix itself must still pass and must not be made green by swallowing the failure or disabling native-image behavior.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:57:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:60:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:71:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/runtime-surface change.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:72:   - Skip this comparison entirely when the new version reports zero dynamic-access calls. A zero-call report gives too little information to judge metadata relevance, so a metadata-entry-count drop for it is not a reliable review signal and must not be reported or escalated.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:88:- The dynamic-access coverage percentage does not drop by more than 20 percentage points between the previous and new tested versions, or a larger drop is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API/runtime surface.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:89:- Total metadata entry counts are not below the 25% severe-drop threshold, or the reduction is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API/runtime surface, or the new version reports zero dynamic-access calls and the metadata-entry-count comparison is skipped.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:96:- The dynamic-access coverage percentage drops by more than 20 percentage points without a credible explanation and replacement coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:97:- Total metadata entry count drops below 25% of the original without a credible explanation for a new version that reports non-zero dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:105:- Total metadata entry count drops below 25% of the original for a new version that reports non-zero dynamic-access calls, but the changed upstream API/runtime surface makes the reduction plausible.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:112:- For metadata entry drops: report only drops where the new version reports non-zero dynamic-access calls and the new total metadata has fewer than 25% as many entries as the previous version's total metadata; cite the old and new counts, and ask for either restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/runtime-surface change. Do not report a metadata entry drop, and do not flag a shallow or off-target test, when the new version reports zero dynamic-access calls, because that signal is not enough to judge metadata relevance.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-javac-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that fixes Java compilation failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the compile fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring the dynamic-access coverage percentage does not drop by more than 20 percentage points between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:20:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate, compared by percentage only. Do not treat changes in absolute covered or total call counts as a drop. The new version should not report a coverage percentage more than 20 percentage points lower than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:21:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:23:- A new version that reports zero dynamic-access calls (for example `dynamicAccess.totalCalls == 0`, or a `{}` `reachability-metadata.json` with no claimed dynamic-access behavior) does not give enough information to judge whether metadata is unnecessary or whether a metadata-entry-count drop is meaningful. Dynamic-access stats can miss metadata required through transitive dependencies. Do not report a metadata-entry-count drop, and do not flag a shallow test or a test that exercises behavior outside the library's responsibility, as a blocking issue or `human-intervention` for such a library. The compile fix itself must still pass and must not be made green by deleting meaningful coverage or disabling native-image behavior.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:55:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:67:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/package change.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:70:   - Skip this comparison entirely when the new version reports zero dynamic-access calls. A zero-call report gives too little information to judge metadata relevance, so a metadata-entry-count drop for it is not a reliable review signal and must not be reported or escalated.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:85:- The dynamic-access coverage percentage does not drop by more than 20 percentage points between the previous and new tested versions, or a larger drop is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API surface.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:86:- Total metadata entry counts are not below the 25% severe-drop threshold, or the reduction is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API surface, or the new version reports zero dynamic-access calls and the metadata-entry-count comparison is skipped.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:93:- The dynamic-access coverage percentage drops by more than 20 percentage points without a credible explanation and replacement coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:94:- Total metadata entry count drops below 25% of the original without a credible explanation for a new version that reports non-zero dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:102:- Total metadata entry count drops below 25% of the original for a new version that reports non-zero dynamic-access calls, but the changed upstream API surface makes the reduction plausible.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:109:- For metadata entry drops: report only drops where the new version reports non-zero dynamic-access calls and the new total metadata has fewer than 25% as many entries as the previous version's total metadata; cite the old and new counts, and ask for either restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/runtime-surface change. Do not report a metadata entry drop, and do not flag a shallow or off-target test, when the new version reports zero dynamic-access calls, because that signal is not enough to judge metadata relevance.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:22:- Require reported dynamic-access coverage above 20% when there are dynamic-access calls to cover. Use the exploded stats files under `stats/<group>/<artifact>/<metadata-version>/stats.json` when available, and block the PR when dynamic-access coverage is 20% or lower or the PR provides no credible dynamic-access coverage evidence for non-zero dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:23:- Treat dynamic-access coverage counts as a minimum gate, not complete metadata evidence. They can miss metadata required through downstream libraries, so do not use high coverage alone to prove that the submitted metadata is complete or necessary.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:24:- Treat `0/0` dynamic-access coverage as a valid no-calls case, not as failed coverage. Do not reject a PR only because the exploded stats report `0/0` dynamic-access calls while the PR adds metadata; those stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:25:- Do not explicitly read or review individual metadata entries. Use the metadata entry count reported in the PR description for the metadata/dynamic-access mismatch check; do not manually count entries from metadata files. When the PR reports both library metadata entries and test-only metadata entries, use their sum as the PR-reported metadata entry count. Only request investigation when the covered dynamic-access call count is at least 75% higher than that PR-reported total. Skip this mismatch check entirely when the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls, because `0/0` does not provide enough information to judge whether the metadata entry count is relevant.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:58:   - For metadata/dynamic-access mismatch checks, use only the metadata entry count reported in the PR description, such as `Metadata entries`, or legacy fields such as `Entries` and `Entries found` in older PRs; add `Test-only metadata entries` when the PR reports it; do not manually count metadata entries from files.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:59:   - Do not run the metadata/dynamic-access mismatch check when the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls. Dynamic-access stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries, so `0/0` is not enough evidence to decide that metadata counts are too high, too low, or irrelevant.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:65:   - Confirm reported dynamic-access coverage is above 20% when the stats include dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:66:   - If the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls and `reachability-metadata.json` is `{}`, that is acceptable as long as the test is library-specific and the scope is otherwise correct.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:67:   - If the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls while adding metadata, do not reject it on that basis alone and do not compare the metadata entry count against dynamic-access calls; dynamic-access stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:68:   - If the stats report 20% coverage or lower for non-zero dynamic-access calls, or no usable coverage signal for claimed dynamic-access behavior, ask for stronger tests or refreshed coverage evidence.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:69:   - Ask for metadata/coverage mismatch investigation only when the PR reports non-zero dynamic-access calls and the covered dynamic-access call count is at least 75% higher than the PR-reported metadata entry count, where the reported count is `Metadata entries` plus `Test-only metadata entries` when both are present. For older PRs, use legacy `Entries` or `Entries found` as the metadata entry count.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:92:  - Reported dynamic-access coverage is 20% or lower for non-zero dynamic-access calls, absent for claimed dynamic-access behavior, or not credible from the diff.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:103:- For insufficient dynamic-access coverage: say that new-library PRs need dynamic-access coverage above 20% when there are dynamic-access calls to cover, and ask for stronger tests or refreshed coverage evidence.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:105:- For metadata/dynamic-access entry mismatch: ask for investigation only when the PR reports non-zero dynamic-access calls and covered dynamic-access calls are at least 75% higher than the PR-reported metadata entry count, summing library and test-only metadata entries when both are reported. Do not manually count or argue from metadata contents, and do not run this check for `0/0` reports.\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:8:import org.graalvm.internal.tck.utils.DynamicAccessUtils\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:82:        // Restrict cacheability to the dynamic-access reporting lane.\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:83:        task.outputs.cacheIf(\"Enabled only when generating dynamic-access reports\") {\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:84:            boolean propertyEnabled = providers.gradleProperty('tck.generateDynamicAccessReport')\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:88:                taskName == \"generateDynamicAccessReport\" || taskName.endsWith(\":generateDynamicAccessReport\")\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:188:String generateDynamicAccessReportVal = providers.gradleProperty('tck.generateDynamicAccessReport').getOrElse(\"false\")\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:189:boolean generateDynamicAccessReportTaskRequested = gradle.startParameter.taskNames.any { taskName ->\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:190:    taskName == \"generateDynamicAccessReport\" || taskName.endsWith(\":generateDynamicAccessReport\")\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:192:boolean generateDynamicAccessReport = generateDynamicAccessReportVal.toBoolean() || generateDynamicAccessReportTaskRequested\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:358:Provider<Directory> dynamicAccessOutputDir = layout.buildDirectory.dir(\"native/nativeTestCompile/dynamic-access\")\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:360:tasks.register(\"generateDynamicAccessReport\") { task ->\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:361:    task.setDescription(\"Builds native tests with dynamic-access tracking and reuses Gradle up-to-date checks when inputs and classpath are unchanged\")\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:634:            if (generateDynamicAccessReport) {\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck.gradle:636:                    DynamicAccessUtils.buildArgsForClasspathEntries(resolveTestedLibraryJars())\n./skills/README.md:35:It covers compile-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: keep the diff scoped to the compile fix, preserve meaningful tests, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/README.md:40:It covers JVM runtime-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: keep the diff scoped to the Java runtime fix, preserve meaningful tests and assertions, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/README.md:45:It covers native-image runtime-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: verify the native path is fixed rather than skipped, keep metadata and test changes scoped, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-native-image-run-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that fixes a native-image runtime failure for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the runtime/native fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring the dynamic-access coverage percentage does not drop by more than 20 percentage points between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair metadata or tests after an existing library version compiles and builds a native image, but the native image fails when the test runs. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library is already supported, so the goal is to restore native-image behavior for a newer version while preserving existing dynamic-access coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate, compared by percentage only. Do not treat changes in absolute covered or total call counts as a drop. The new version should not report a coverage percentage more than 20 percentage points lower than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:20:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:22:- A new version that reports zero dynamic-access calls (for example `dynamicAccess.totalCalls == 0`, or a `{}` `reachability-metadata.json` with no claimed dynamic-access behavior) does not give enough information to judge whether metadata is unnecessary or whether a metadata-entry-count drop is meaningful. Dynamic-access stats can miss metadata required through transitive dependencies. Do not report a metadata-entry-count drop, and do not flag a shallow test or a test that exercises behavior outside the library's responsibility, as a blocking issue or `human-intervention` for such a library. The native-image runtime fix itself must still pass and must not be made green by skipping the native path or disabling native-image behavior.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:54:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:57:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - If metadata fixes make the native run pass but the dynamic-access coverage percentage drops by more than 20 percentage points, ask for restored coverage first. Passing native execution is not enough by itself.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:67:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/package change.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:70:   - Skip this comparison entirely when the new version reports zero dynamic-access calls. A zero-call report gives too little information to judge metadata relevance, so a metadata-entry-count drop for it is not a reliable review signal and must not be reported or escalated.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:85:- The dynamic-access coverage percentage does not drop by more than 20 percentage points between the previous and new tested versions, or a larger drop is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API surface.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:86:- Total metadata entry counts are not below the 25% severe-drop threshold, or the reduction is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API surface, or the new version reports zero dynamic-access calls and the metadata-entry-count comparison is skipped.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:92:- The dynamic-access coverage percentage drops by more than 20 percentage points without a credible explanation and replacement coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:93:- Total metadata entry count drops below 25% of the original without a credible explanation for a new version that reports non-zero dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:102:- Total metadata entry count drops below 25% of the original for a new version that reports non-zero dynamic-access calls, but the changed upstream API surface makes the reduction plausible.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:109:- For metadata entry drops: report only drops where the new version reports non-zero dynamic-access calls and the new total metadata has fewer than 25% as many entries as the previous version's total metadata; cite the old and new counts, and ask for either restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/runtime-surface change. Do not report a metadata entry drop, and do not flag a shallow or off-target test, when the new version reports zero dynamic-access calls, because that signal is not enough to judge metadata relevance.\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/test/java/org/graalvm/internal/tck/utils/DynamicAccessUtilsTests.java:19:class DynamicAccessUtilsTests {\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/test/java/org/graalvm/internal/